</arg></template><space/></paragraph><paragraph><bold>Anbar</bold><space/>(<bold><template><target>lang</target><arg>ar</arg><arg>Ø§Ù„Ø£Ù†Ø¨Ø§Ø±</arg></template></bold>) was a town in<space/><link><target>Iraq</target></link>, at lat. 33 deg. 22' N., long. 43 deg. 49' E, on the east bank of the<space/><link><target>Euphrates</target></link>, just south of the Nahr 'Isa, or Sakhlawieh<space/><link><target>canal</target></link>, the northernmost of the canals connecting that river with the<space/><link><target>Tigris</target></link>.</paragraph><heading level='2'>History</heading><paragraph>Anbar was originally called<space/><bold>Prz-pr</bold><space/>or<space/><bold>Prz-buhr</bold><space/>(from<space/><template><target>lang-pal</target><arg>ğ­¯ğ­¥ğ­©ğ­¥ğ­¦ğ­±ğ­§ğ­¯ğ­¥ğ­§ğ­¥ğ­©</arg></template>, meaning &quot;Victorious Shapur&quot;; in<space/><template><target>lang-xpr</target><arg>ğ­ğ­“ğ­‚ğ­…ğ­†ğ­”ğ­‡ğ­ğ­…ğ­‡ğ­“</arg></template><space/><italics>prgwzhypwhr</italics>; in<space/><template><target>lang-arc</target><arg>×¤×™×¨×•×– ×©×‘×•×¨</arg></template>), and became known as<space/><bold>Perisapora</bold><space/>or<space/><bold>Pirisabora</bold><space/>to the Greeks and Romans. The city was founded ca. 350 by the<space/><link><target>Sassanid Empire</target><part>Sassanid Persian</part></link><space/>king<space/><link><target>Shapur II</target></link>, and located in the Sassanid province of<space/><link><target>Asristn</target></link>. Perisapora was sacked and burned by Emperor<space/><link><target>Julian the Apostate</target><part>Julian</part></link><space/>in April 363, during<space/><link><target>Julian's Persian expedition</target><part>his invasion</part></link><space/>of the<space/><link><target>Sassanid Empire</target></link>.<extension extension_name='ref'>G. W. Bowersock,<space/><italics>Julian the Apostate</italics>, (Harvard University Press, 1978), 112.</extension><space/>The town became a refuge for the<space/><link><target>Arab</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Christianity</target><part>Christian</part></link>, and<space/><link><target>Jew</target><trail>ish</trail></link><space/>colonies of that region.<template><target>sfn</target><arg>Peters</arg><arg>1911</arg></template><space/>According to medieval Arabic sources, most of the inhabitants of the town migrated north to find the city of<space/><link><target>Hdatta</target></link><space/>south of<space/><link><target>Mosul</target></link>.<extension extension_name='ref' name="EOI"><template><target>cite encyclopedia</target><arg name="last"><space/>Lewis<space/></arg><arg name="first"><space/>Bernard<space/></arg><arg name="authorlink"><space/>Bernard Lewis<space/></arg><arg name="editor"><space/>Hertzfeld, E<space/></arg><arg name="encyclopedia"><space/>Encyclopaedia of Islam<space/></arg><arg name="isbn"><space/>9789004081185<space/></arg><arg name="title"><space/>á¸¤adÄ«tÌ²a<space/></arg><arg name="url"><space/>http://books.google.com/books?id</arg><arg name="accessdate"><space/>12 October 2012<space/></arg><arg name="edition"><space/>Second<space/></arg><arg name="year"><space/>1986<space/></arg><arg name="publisher"><space/>BRILL<space/></arg><arg name="volume"><space/>3<space/></arg><arg name="pages"><space/>29<space/></arg></template></extension></paragraph><paragraph>Anbar was adjacent or identical to the<space/><link><target>History of the Jews in Iraq#Babylonia as the center of Judaism</target><part>Babylonian Jewish</part></link><space/>center of<space/><link><target>Nehardea</target></link><space/>(<template><target>lang-arc</target><arg>× ×”×¨×“×¢×</arg></template>), and lies a short distance from the present-day town of<space/><link><target>Fallujah</target></link>, formerly the<space/><link><target>History of the Jews in Iraq#Babylonia as the center of Judaism</target><part>Babylonian Jewish</part></link><space/>center of<space/><link><target>Pumbeditha</target></link><space/>(<template><target>lang-arc</target><arg>×¤×•××‘×“×™×ª×</arg></template>).</paragraph><paragraph>The name of the town was then changed to<space/><italics>Anbar</italics><space/>(<link><target>Middle Persian</target></link><space/>word for &quot;<link><target>granaries</target></link>&quot;).<space/><link><target>As-Saffah</target><part>Abu al-Abbas as-Saffah</part></link>, the founder of the<space/><link><target>Abbasid</target></link><space/>caliphate, made it his capital, and such it remained until the founding of<space/><link><target>Baghdad</target></link><space/>in 762. It continued to be a place of much importance throughout the Abbasid period.<template><target>sfn</target><arg>Peters</arg><arg>1911</arg></template></paragraph><paragraph>Anbar used to host an<space/><link><target>Assyrian people</target><part>Assyrian</part></link><space/>community from the fifth century: the town was the seat of a bishopric of the<space/><link><target>Church of the East</target></link>. The names of 14 of its bishops of the period 4861074 are known, three of whom became patriarchs.<extension extension_name='ref'>Michel Lequien,<space/><link type='external' href='http://books.google.com/books?id=86weAemI-e4C&amp;amp;printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&amp;amp;q&amp;amp;f=false'>''Oriens christianus in quatuor Patriarchatus digestus''</link>, Paris 1740, Vol. II, coll. 1171-1174</extension><space/>No longer a residential bishopric, Anbar is today listed by the<space/><link><target>Catholic Church</target></link><space/>as a<space/><link><target>titular see</target></link><space/>of the<space/><link><target>Chaldean Catholic Church</target></link>.<extension extension_name='ref'><italics>Annuario Pontificio 2013</italics><space/>(Libreria Editrice Vaticana 2013 ISBN 978-88-209-9070-1), p. 832</extension></paragraph><heading level='2'>Today</heading><paragraph>It is now entirely deserted, occupied only by mounds of ruins, whose great number indicate the city's former importance.<template><target>sfn</target><arg>Peters</arg><arg>1911</arg></template></paragraph><heading level='2'>See also</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Nehardea</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Fallujah</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Pumbeditha</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Ctesiphon</target></link></listitem></list><heading level='2'>References</heading><paragraph><template><target>reflist</target></template></paragraph><list type='def'><listitem><defkey>Attribution</defkey></listitem></list><list type='bullet'><listitem><template><target>EB1911</target><arg name="first">John Punnett<space/></arg><arg name="last">Peters</arg><arg name="wstitle">Anbar</arg></template></listitem></list><paragraph><template><target>coord</target><arg>33</arg><arg>22</arg><arg>43</arg><arg>N</arg><arg>43</arg><arg>42</arg><arg>57</arg><arg>E</arg><arg name="display">title</arg><arg>source:frwiki</arg></template></paragraph><paragraph><template><target>DEFAULTSORT:Anbar (Town)</target></template><link><target>Category:Populated places in Al Anbar Governorate</target></link><link><target>Category:Sasanian cities</target></link></paragraph></article>